05715nam a22007815i 9780292769816DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211983txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927698167 a10.7560/7757632doi  a(DE-B1597)586979  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHT123.5.A163bS93 1983 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a307.7/64/097321900aSunbelt Cities :bPolitics and Growth since World War II /ced. by Richard M. Bernard, Bradley Robert Rice. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1983  a1 online resource (358 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1 INTRODUCTION -- t2 ATLANTA: IF DIXIE WERE ATLANTA -- t3 MIAMI: THE ETHNIC CAULDRON -- t4 NEW ORLEANS: SUNBELT IN THE SWAMP -- t5 TAMPA: FROM HELL HOLE TO THE GOOD LIFE -- t6 DALLAS-FORT: WORTH MARKETING THE METROPLEX -- t7 HOUSTON: THE GOLDEN BUCKLE OF THE SUNBELT -- t8 OKLAHOMA: CITY BOOMING SOONER -- t9 SAN ANTONIO: THE VICISSITUDES OF BOOSTERISM -- t10 ALBUQUERQUE: CITY AT A CROSSROADS -- t11 LOS ANGELES: IMPROBABLE LOS ANGELES -- t12 PHOENIX THE DESERT METROPOLIS -- t13 SAN DIEGO: THE ANTI-CITY -- tCONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1940 and 1980, the Sunbelt region of the United States grew in population by 112 percent, while the older, graying Northeast and Midwest together grew by only 42 percent. Phoenix expanded by an astonishing 1,138 percent. San Diego, Houston, Dallas–Fort Worth, Tampa, Miami, and Atlanta quadrupled in size. Even a Sunbelt laggard such as New Orleans more than doubled its population. Sunbelt Cities brings together a collection of outstanding original essays on the growth and late-twentieth-century political development of the major metropolitan areas below the thirty-seventh parallel. The cities surveyed are Albuquerque, Atlanta, Dallas–Fort Worth, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, New Orleans, Oklahoma City, Phoenix, San Antonio, San Diego, and Tampa. Each author examines the economic and social causes of postwar population growth in the city under consideration and the resulting changes in its political climate. Major causes of growth such as changing economic conditions, industrial recruitment, lifestyle preferences, and climate are discussed. Particular attention is paid to the role of the federal government, especially the Pentagon, in encouraging development in the Sunbelt. Describing characteristic political developments of many of these cities, the authors note shifting political alliances, the ouster of machines and business elites from political power, and the rise of minority and neighborhood groups in local politics. Sunbelt Cities is the first full-scale scholarly examination of the region popularly conceived as the Sunbelt. As one of the first works to thoroughly examine a wide range of cities within the region, it has served as a standard reference on the area for some time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCities and townszSunbelt States. 0aCities and towns--Sunbelt States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBernard, Richard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Richard M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorso, Anthony W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Arnold R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Barry J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuckingham, Bradford, econtributor.4c